You can trace any inserted row to the exact (sub)partition and tablespace it landed in by grabbing its ROWID at insert time, then resolving that ROWID to the owning segment.

A) For the table row (which heap subpartition & tablespace?)
-- 1) Insert and capture the rowid
VAR rid ROWID
INSERT INTO GD.CIM_OFM_SMG6_LOGGING
  (TRACE_ID, ALIAS, AUDIT_CREATE_DATE, SMG3_LOGGING_DATA, FILTRATION_JSON_DATA)
VALUES
  (SYS_GUID(), 'ASIA', SYSTIMESTAMP, RPAD('X', 1024), RPAD('Y', 1024))
RETURNING ROWID INTO :rid;

-- 2) Resolve rowid -> object/subobject (partition/subpartition) -> tablespace
SELECT o.owner,
       o.object_name       AS table_name,
       o.subobject_name    AS part_or_subpart,   -- partition or SUBPARTITION name
       s.segment_type,
       s.tablespace_name
FROM   dba_objects  o
LEFT JOIN dba_segments s
       ON s.owner = o.owner
      AND s.segment_name = o.object_name
      AND NVL(s.partition_name,'-') = NVL(o.subobject_name,'-')
WHERE  o.data_object_id = DBMS_ROWID.ROWID_OBJECT(:rid);


This tells you exactly which (sub)partition the row is in and the tablespace of that heap segment.

B) For the row’s LOB columns (which LOB subpartition & tablespace?)

Once you know the table subpartition name from step A (say it’s SP0_2025_08_24), map that to the LOB subpartition rows:

-- Replace :subp with the subpartition name from step A
VAR subp VARCHAR2(128)
EXEC :subp := '<<SUBPARTITION_NAME_FROM_STEP_A>>';

-- LOB #1
SELECT lsp.table_owner, lsp.table_name, lsp.column_name,
       lsp.subpartition_name, lsp.lob_name, lsp.tablespace_name
FROM   dba_lob_subpartitions lsp
WHERE  lsp.table_owner      = 'GD'
  AND  lsp.table_name       = 'CIM_OFM_SMG6_LOGGING'
  AND  lsp.column_name      = 'SMG3_LOGGING_DATA'
  AND  lsp.subpartition_name= :subp;

-- LOB #2
SELECT lsp.table_owner, lsp.table_name, lsp.column_name,
       lsp.subpartition_name, lsp.lob_name, lsp.tablespace_name
FROM   dba_lob_subpartitions lsp
WHERE  lsp.table_owner      = 'GD'
  AND  lsp.table_name       = 'CIM_OFM_SMG6_LOGGING'
  AND  lsp.column_name      = 'FILTRATION_JSON_DATA'
  AND  lsp.subpartition_name= :subp;


These queries show the LOB subpartition and its tablespace (e.g., GD_LOB_05 / GD_LOB_06), i.e., where the CLOB/BLOB bytes are stored.
